### Star Wars API - HTTP Request Examples
### This file contains examples for testing the Star Wars API endpoints
### Use with VS Code REST Client extension

@baseUrl = http://localhost:3000/api


### =============================================================================
### SEARCH ENDPOINTS
### =============================================================================

### Search across all categories
GET {{baseUrl}}/search?query=Luke

### Search across all categories with different term
GET {{baseUrl}}/search?query=Skywalker

### Search across all categories with vehicle term
GET {{baseUrl}}/search?query=X-wing

### Search across all categories with planet term
GET {{baseUrl}}/search?query=Yoda

### Search in specific category - People
GET {{baseUrl}}/search/people?query=Skywalker

### Search in specific category - Films
GET {{baseUrl}}/search/films?query=Empire

### Search in specific category - Starships
GET {{baseUrl}}/search/starships?query=Millennium

### Search in specific category - Vehicles
GET {{baseUrl}}/search/vehicles?query=Speeder

### Search in specific category - Species
GET {{baseUrl}}/search/species?query=Human

### Search in specific category - Planets
GET {{baseUrl}}/search/planets?query=Coruscant

### Search with empty query (should return error)
GET {{baseUrl}}/search?query=

### Search in invalid category (should return error)
GET {{baseUrl}}/search/invalid?query=test

### Search in specific category - Films
GET {{baseUrl}}/search/films?query=Empire

### Search in specific category - People
GET {{baseUrl}}/search/people?query=Skywalker

### Search people by ID
GET {{baseUrl}}/people/20

### Search people by ID (should return error)
GET {{baseUrl}}/people/100

### Search films by ID
GET {{baseUrl}}/films/1

### Search films by ID (should return error)
GET {{baseUrl}}/films/100

### =============================================================================
### STATS ENDPOINTS
### =============================================================================

### Get comprehensive API statistics
GET {{baseUrl}}/stats

### =============================================================================
### ERROR SCENARIOS
### =============================================================================

### Missing query parameter (should return 400)
GET {{baseUrl}}/search

### Invalid category (should return 400)
GET {{baseUrl}}/search/invalid-category?query=test

### Non-existent endpoint (should return 404)
GET {{baseUrl}}/non-existent

### =============================================================================
### TESTING SEQUENCE
### =============================================================================

### 1. Perform a search
GET {{baseUrl}}/search?query=Luke

### 2. Get statistics
GET {{baseUrl}}/stats

### 3. Get statistics again (should recalculate)
GET {{baseUrl}}/stats

### =============================================================================
### VARIABLES AND ENVIRONMENTS
### =============================================================================

### You can create different environments by creating .env files:
### .env.development, .env.production, etc.

### Example variables that can be used:
# @baseUrl = http://localhost:3000/api
# @searchTerm = Luke
# @category = people

### Then use them in requests:
# GET {{baseUrl}}/search?query={{searchTerm}}
# GET {{baseUrl}}/search/{{category}}?query={{searchTerm}}

### =============================================================================
### TIPS FOR REST CLIENT
### =============================================================================

### 1. Click "Send Request" above each request to execute it
### 2. Use Ctrl+Click (Cmd+Click on Mac) on request URLs to open in browser
### 3. Results appear in a separate panel to the right
### 4. You can save responses to files using > symbol
### 5. Use variables to avoid repetition
### 6. Create separate environments for different configurations

### Example of saving response to file:
# GET {{baseUrl}}/search?query=Luke
# >> ./responses/luke-search.json

### Example of using environment variables:
# ### Development environment
# @baseUrl = http://localhost:3000/api
# 
# ### Production environment
# @baseUrl = https://api.starwars.example.com/api

